ğŸ“– **Description:**
    The `debdiff-apply` command is used to apply changes from a `diff.gz` file (created by `debdiff`) to the original source code. In other words, it adds the changes specified in the diff file to the original code. This command is often used to apply Debian patches.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ğŸ”¹ `-p[number]` --> âœ‚ï¸ The number of directories to strip from the beginning of the file names in the diff file. For example, `-p1` strips one directory. The default value is `-p1` if this option is not given.
    ğŸ”¹ `--no-backup` --> ğŸš« Do not create backups of the original files before applying the changes. By default, backups are created.
    ğŸ”¹ `--version`  --> â„¹ï¸  Display version information.
    ğŸ”¹ `--help` --> â“ Display help information.

ğŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ debdiff-apply patch.diff.gz

    ğŸ”¹ Apply changes from the `patch.diff.gz` file using the default path stripping (`-p1`).

    $ debdiff-apply -p0 patch.diff.gz

    ğŸ”¹ Apply changes from the `patch.diff.gz` file without stripping any directories from the path.

    $ debdiff-apply --no-backup patch.diff.gz

    ğŸ”¹ Apply changes from the `patch.diff.gz` file without creating backups of the original files.

âœ… **Simple Example:**

